This approach iterates over every registered network adapter to extract both IPv4 and IPv6 configurations. It applies specific filtering logic to exclude common local management IP ranges like 169.254/16 (IPv4) and fe80::/32 or any addresses including interface names for IPv6.

```python
def get_addresses():
    """
    Get all IP addresses.

    Returns list of addresses.
    """
    addresses = set()

    for iface in ifaddr.get_adapters():
        for addr in iface.ips:
            # Filter out link-local addresses.
            if addr.is_IPv4:
                ip = addr.ip

                if not ip.startswith('169.254.'):
                    addresses.add(ip)
            elif addr.is_IPv6:
                # Sometimes, IPv6 addresses will have the interface name
                # appended, e.g. %eth0. Handle that.
                ip = addr.ip[0].split('%')[0].lower()

                if not ip.startswith('fe80:'):
                    addresses.add('[{}]'.format(ip))

    return sorted(list(addresses))
```

The code handles tricky edge cases, such as cleaning up interface names appended to IPv6 addresses. Remember that this relies on the availability and correct configuration of a network identity provider (`ifaddr` in this case).
